  "teacher_notes": {
    "objective": "Students will be able to identify and name 15 common food items in English, understand their Spanish equivalents, and use simple sentences to express preferences.",
    "suggested_use": "Introduce vocabulary using flashcards and realia. Use the mini-book for shared reading and repeated exposure. Worksheets can be used for independent practice, small group work, or as homework. Encourage students to point to pictures and repeat words. Integrate into daily routines (e.g., during snack time).",
    "materials_needed": [
      "Printed vocabulary cards (for each food item)",
      "Real food items or toy food (if available)",
      "Crayons/markers",
      "Pencils",
      "Scissors (for mini-book assembly)",
      "Glue sticks (for mini-book assembly)"
    ],
    "differentiation_tips": [
      "**For beginners:** Focus on 5-7 core words. Provide heavy visual support and model pronunciation repeatedly. Use total physical response (TPR) activities.",
      "**For developing learners:** Encourage students to use the words in simple sentences (e.g., 'I like apples.'). Have them identify foods by color or category (e.g., 'fruit').",
      "**For advanced learners:** Challenge them to describe the foods (e.g., 'The apple is red and sweet.'). Introduce new related vocabulary (e.g., 'breakfast', 'lunch', 'dinner'). Ask them to draw their favorite food and label it."
    ]
  },
